olitics-live-with-andrew-sparrow\">Politics live with Andrew Sparrow</a>.</p>","bylineImageUrl":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/contributor/2014/5/6/1399377991807/Andrew-Sparrow.jpg","bylineLargeImageUrl":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/contributor/2014/5/6/1399378038371/Andrew-Sparrow-R.png","firstName":"andrew","lastName":"sparrow","twitterHandle":"AndrewSparrow"}],"fields":{"headline":"Theresa May's statement on the UK Border Agency: Politics live blog","standfirst":"<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/blog/2013/mar/26/hunt-mid-staffs-osborne-budget-live#block-51518ce195cbbc3a59c25e72\">• Lunchtime summary</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/blog/2013/mar/26/hunt-mid-staffs-osborne-budget-live#block-5151a02d95cbbc3a59c25e88\">• Hunt's statement on Mid Staffs - Main points</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/blog/2013/mar/26/hunt-mid-staffs-osborne-budget-live#block-5151b6b695cbbc3a59c25ea9\">• May's statement on breaking up UKBA - Summary</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/blog/2013/mar/26/hunt-mid-staffs-osborne-budget-live#block-5151d065b5791610ecc9c360\">• Afternoon summary</a>","trailText":"<p><strong>Andrew Sparrow</strong>'s rolling coverage of all the day's political developments as they happen, including Jeremy Hunt presenting the government's response to the Mid Staffs report and the Treasury committee questioning George Osborne on the budget</p>","byline":"Andrew Sparrow","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-ef51dcd7-1772-42a7-808f-79cae154ce87\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/3/26/1364306665518/5462c650-a5de-44a3-beda-54372b75bce2-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Theresa May is making a statement about the UK Border Agency.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Theresa May is making a statement about the UK Border Agency. Photograph: David Pearson/Rex Features</span> </figcaption> </figure>","body":"<div id=\"block-5151d065b5791610ecc9c360\" class=\"block is-summary\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T16:44:21.666Z\">4.44pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">Afternoon summary</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2013/mar/26/uk-border-agency-broken-up\">Theresa May, the home secretary, has announced that the troubled UK Border Agency is to be abolished and brought back within the Home Office</a>.</strong> In an internal memo that has been leaked and reported by the Press Association, Mark Sedwill, the Home Office permanent secretary, said the reorganisation would have little impact on most staff.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Most of us will still be doing the same job in the same place with the same colleagues for the same boss and with the same mission to keep Britain&apos;s streets safe and our borders secure.</p> </blockquote> <p><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/2013/mar/26/failing-hospitals-nhs-jeremy-hunt\">Jeremy Hunt, the health secretary, has announced that failing hospitals will be named and shamed and NHS managers responsible for failures will be barred from working in the health service under government plans to ensure a Mid Staffs-style care scandal never happens again</a>.</strong></p> <p><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-21936366\">George Osborne has criticised the handling of the Cyprus crisis by European and Cypriot authorities</a>.</strong> Giving evidence to the Commons Treasury committee, he said that initial plans to impose a levy on all bank deposits was a &quot;mistake&quot; and had &quot;not been well handled&quot;. There is more about Osborne&apos;s comments on Cyprus <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2013/mar/26/eurozone-crisis-cyprus-banks#block-5151bf0a95cbbc3a59c25eae\">on our business live blog.</a></p> <p><strong>• Vince Cable has said that in principle he is in favour of a financial transaction tax.</strong> Although the government is opposing a European attempt to introduce one, the Lib Dem business secretary told a committee of MPs that he was &quot;quite disposed&quot; to using a financial transaction tax as a way of trying to change behaviour in the financial sector.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>I have got no objection to the ... well, I would put it more positively - I think there is a case if you are trying to change behaviour from using a market instrument of that kind to make it happen ...</p> <p>The reason why the British government has been pretty negative about it is mainly on grounds of practicality and the other reason we have been sceptical about it, of course, is that most of the revenue would be generated in the UK and under the European Union&apos;s proposal would be repatriated to Brussels, which understandably, we are not too happy about.</p> </blockquote> <p><strong>• David Cameron has indicated that he will not consider devolving power over corporation tax to Northern Ireland until after the referendum on Scottish independence in September 2014.</strong> After discussing the matter at Number 10 with Cameron, Peter Robinson, Northern Ireland&apos;s first minster, and Martin McGuinness, the deputy first minister, both expressed disappointment. McGuinness said Cameron had made it &quot;absolutely clear&quot; that there would not be a decision until after the Scottish referendum.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>It&apos;s very, very clear from the meeting that the whole issue of the referendum in Scotland is playing in big time to this debate on corporation tax and I think it is absolutely clear that no decision will be taken on this issue this side of the Scottish referendum. I think we have to face that reality.</p> </blockquote> <p><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/2013/mar/26/foreign-lawsuits-uk-legal-fees\">Chris Grayling, the justice secretary, has announced a review that could lead to higher court fees for foreign businessmen and Russian oligarchs who pursue their multimillion-pound disputes in British courts</a>.</strong></p> <p><strong>• A council has launched a misconduct investigation into the Lib Dem MP Mike Hancock.</strong> As the Press Association reports, Hancock, who sits on Portsmouth City Council as well as being MP for Portsmouth South, is to be subjected to the three-month probe following an allegation made to the council. The local authority&apos;s governance and audit and standards committee has assessed the complaint and ordered the investigation by an independent lawyer. Michael Lawther, solicitor for Portsmouth City Council, said: &quot;A sub-committee of Portsmouth City Council today decided to refer a complaint against Cllr Mike Hancock for investigation.&quot; The move comes as a &quot;vulnerable&quot; constituent is suing the MP in the High Court, accusing him of sexual assault after she contacted him for help in a neighbour dispute. Hancock, who vigorously denied the claims, was arrested by police over the allegations in 2010 but no action was taken as the Crown Prosecution Service said there was insufficient evidence for a prosecution. A spokesman for Hancock said that the allegations had been investigated by the police and that no action had been taken and that Hancock strongly denied breaking the code of conduct.</p> <p><strong>• Unions, politicians, comedians and protest groups have joined forces to launch a new campaign against the government&apos;s spending cuts.</strong> As the Press Association reports, <a href=\"http://www.coalitionofresistance.org.uk/\">the People&apos;s Assembly</a> is backed by Unite, the National Union of Teachers, the Public and Commercial Services union, Labour and Green MPs and activists, with the aim of launching &quot;mass resistance&quot; to austerity. A rally will be held in June and meetings will be organised across the UK to draw as many people as possible into the campaign against cuts ranging from library closures to welfare reforms.</p> <p><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.politicshome.com/uk/article/75276/lougton_v_toryeducation_this_time_its_war%3F.html\">The controversial Tory education Twitter feed has accused the former education minister Tim Loughton of lying about an incident that happened in the Department for Education when he was a minister</a>.</strong> The account is thought to be linked to Michael Gove&apos;s advisers. <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2013/feb/02/michael-gove-department-twitter-attacks\">They have dismissed claims that they are involved, although, when the Observer invited them to provide a firm denial, they declined. </a></p> <p><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-21937193\">Martha Lane Fox has taken her seat in the House of Lords</a>.</strong></p> <p>That&apos;s all from me for today.</p> <p>Thanks for the comments.</p> </div>   <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T16:46:57.881Z\">at 4.46pm GMT</time></p>  </div> <div id=\"block-5151c424b5795d794abf44eb\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T15:52:05.085Z\">3.52pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Here&apos;s a short afternoon reading list.</p> <p><a href=\"http://labourlist.org/2013/03/labour-hires-obamas-backroom-brit-as-it-seeks-to-make-2015-the-digital-election/\">• Mark Ferguson at LabourList says the Labour party has hired the expert who ran Digital Rapid Response for Obama for America.</a></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>If you believe that online campaigning matters (I do) and that the Labour Party has historically lagged behind the Tories on investment in this area (I certainly do), then you’ll see this as a significant upgrade in the party’s capacity. I won’t be expecting fireworks straight away – but I’d expect a noticeable improvement in the party’s online offering in the coming months.</p> </blockquote> <p><a href=\"http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/alex-massie/2013/03/the-scottish-tories-cross-their-rubicon/\">• Alex Massie at the Spectator says Ruth Davidson&apos;s speech today - see 12.13pm - has moved the Scottish Conservatives towards embracing proper fiscal home rule.</a></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>The nationalists will instinctively suggest this is only weak toast and little more than a renewed outbreak of <em>Douglas-Homeism</em> on the Tory benches. We have been here before. Perhaps. But Davidson’s speech helps give the lie to the idea that constitutional change can only be achieved with a vote for independence. It suits the SNP to peddle that line but it suffers from being untrue.</p> <p>Granted, there remain questions. The Scottish Tories may be willing to make a manifesto commitment to some form of fiscal autonomy but that does not compel their Westminster brethren to look so fondly upon the notion.</p> <p>And there’s one rub: this is a British matter too, one that has obvious consequences south of the Tweed. But is Westminster - far less England at large – paying attention? I suspect not. There was not a cheap about Davidson’s speech in this morning’s email from <em>Conservative Home</em>. Nor have the London papers devoted much attention to this development.</p> <p>But perhaps they should. Because the Tweed seems broader and deeper than ever. A rather more formidable barrier, in fact, than the piddling Rubicon of ancient renown. Scotland is presently semi-detached from the rest of the United Kingdom and Davidson’s speech today both confirms that and makes it clear that even the Scottish Tories now accept there’s no going back.</p> </blockquote> </div>   <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T15:53:11.137Z\">at 3.53pm GMT</time></p>  </div> <div id=\"block-5151bd91b5795d794abf44e6\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T15:24:01.686Z\">3.24pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>Keith Vaz,</strong> the chair of the Commons home affairs committee, has put out this statement about the UKBA.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>The home secretary has done the right thing in putting the UK Backlog Agency out of its misery.</p> <p>As yesterday&apos;s home affairs committee report shows, the organisation is not fit for purpose.</p> <p>However, this cannot be an excuse not to clear the backlogs, which stand at a third of a million cases.</p> <p>Ministers are now on the front line.</p> <p>Proper accountability and scrutiny of our immigration system must continue, and it will need effective and strong leadership if the home office is serious about having a fully functional immigration system.</p> </blockquote> <p>The home affairs committee is now taking evidence about this from Mark Sedwill, permanent secretary at the Home Office, Rob Whiteman, the UKBA chief executive, and Simon Hayes, acting directo of the UKBA&apos;s international directorate.</p> <p>The BBC&apos;s Norman Smith is monitoring it.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/BBCNormanS/status/316565666041823232\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Shake up of <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search/%23UKBA\">#UKBA</a> to take effect from Monday</p>&mdash; norman smith (@BBCNormanS) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/BBCNormanS/status/316565666041823232\">March 26, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/BBCNormanS/status/316567058018099200\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Perm Secretary at Home Office Mark Sedwill says despite <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search/%23UKBA\">#UKBA</a> changes \"most of us will be doing same job in same place\"</p>&mdash; norman smith (@BBCNormanS) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/BBCNormanS/status/316567058018099200\">March 26, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5151b6b695cbbc3a59c25ea9\" class=\"block is-summary\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T14:54:46.726Z\">2.54pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">May's statement on breaking up the UK Border Agency - Summary</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Here&apos;s a summary of the main points in Theresa May&apos;s opening statement, with all the key quotes.</p> <p><strong>• May announced that the UK Border Agency (UKBA) was being split up.</strong></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>The government is splitting up the UK Border Agency. In its place will be an immigration and visa service and an immigration law enforcement organisation. By creating two entities instead of one, we will be able to create distinct cultures. First, a high-volume service that makes high-quality decisions about who comes here, with a culture of customer satisfaction for businessmen and visitors who want to come here legally. And second, an organisation that has law enforcement at its heart and gets tough on those who break our immigration laws.</p> </blockquote> <p><strong>• She said the two new units would be part of the Home Office because giving UKBA agency status was a mistake.</strong></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>UKBA was given agency status in order to keep its work at an arm&apos;s length from ministers. That was wrong. It created a closed, secretive and defensive culture. So I can tell the House that the new entities will not have agency status and will sit in the Home Office, reporting to ministers.</p> </blockquote> <p><strong>• She said she was setting up a new immigration strategic oversight board in the Home Office, chaired by the permanent secretary, Mark Sedwill.</strong></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>In making these changes it is important that we do not simply create new silos. And that is why we are creating a strategic oversight board for all the constituent organisations in the immigration system — immigration policy, the Passport Service, Border Force and the two new entities we are creating — and that oversight board will be chaired by the Home Office permanent secretary.</p> </blockquote> <p><strong>• She said she was setting up a programme to modernise immigration IT.</strong></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>UKBA&apos;s IT systems are often incompatible and are not reliable enough. They require manual data entry instead of automated data collection, and they often involve paper files instead of modern electronic case management. So I have asked the permanent secretary and Home Office Board to produce a new plan, building on the work done by Rob Whiteman, UKBA&apos;s chief executive, to modernise IT across the whole immigration system.</p> </blockquote> <p><strong>• She said she would introduce an immigration bill in the next session of parliament to make removing illegal immigrants easier.</strong></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>The Agency is often caught up in a vicious cycle of complex law and poor enforcement of its own policies, which makes it harder to remove people who are here illegally. That is why I intend to bring forward an Immigration bill in the next session of parliament that will address some of these problems.</p> </blockquote> <p><strong>• She said UKBA was being split up because its performance was &quot;not good enough&quot;.</strong></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>The Agency struggles with the volume of its casework, which has led to historical backlogs running into the hundreds of thousands. The number of illegal immigrants removed does not keep up with the number of people who are here illegally. And while the visa operation is internationally competitive, it could and should get better still. The home affairs select committee has published many critical reports about UKBA&apos;s performance. As I have said to the House before, the Agency has been a troubled organisation since it was formed in 2008, and its performance is not good enough.</p> </blockquote> <p><strong>• She said Labour&apos;s decision to allow mass immigration was partly to blame of UKBA&apos;s problems.</strong></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>In truth, the Agency was not set up to absorb the level of mass immigration that we saw under the last government. This meant that the Agency has never had the space to modernise its structures and systems and get on top of its workload.</p> </blockquote> <p><strong>• She said UKBA had four specific problems.</strong></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>I believe the Agency&apos;s problems boil down to four main issues. First, the sheer size of the Agency means it has conflicting cultures, and all too often focuses on the crisis in hand at the expense of other important work. Second, its lack of transparency and accountability. Third, its inadequate IT systems. And fourth, the policy and legal framework within which it has to operate.</p> </blockquote> </div>   <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T14:54:59.130Z\">at 2.54pm GMT</time></p>  </div> <div id=\"block-5151b376b5795d794abf44de\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T14:40:54.544Z\">2.40pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>May&apos;s statement is now over. </p> <p>I&apos;ve got a text of her opening remarks, and I will post a summary soon.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5151b29895cbbc3a59c25ea0\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T14:37:12.517Z\">2.37pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>Jane Ellison</strong>, a Conservative, asks for an assurance that high-performing business people will be able to get visas quickly.</p> <p>May says that is her plan. In India a service is being set up that will allow visas to be issued in 24 hours.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5151b26195cbbc3a59c25e9e\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T14:36:17.295Z\">2.36pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>May says the government inherited a backlog of 500,000 asylum cases. That backlog has been cleared, she says.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5151b24295cbbc3a59c25e9d\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T14:35:46.445Z\">2.35pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>Alec Shelbrooke</strong>, a Conservative, says many of his constituents in Elmet and Rothwell work at UKBA. What difference will this announcement make to them?</p> <p>May says she is not proposing to close any sites. Many UKBA staff will carry on doing the work they are doing now without any change, she says.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5151b1d8b5795d794abf44dd\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T14:34:00.982Z\">2.34pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>Shailesh Vara</strong>, a Conservative, says anything Yvette Cooper says on immigration will have no credibility until she apologises for the shambles left by Labour.</p> <p>John Bercow, the Speaker, says May should not respond because she is not responsible for Labour policy.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5151b00e95cbbc3a59c25e9a\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T14:26:22.438Z\">2.26pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Labour&apos;s <strong>Steve McCabe</strong> welcomes the announcement. He asks what May will do to ensure that documents do not go missing during the reorganisation, as usually happens.</p> <p>May thanks McCabe for his comment. He has more of a policy than the Labour front bench, she says. She says she wants to ensure files do not go missing.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5151af17b5795d794abf44dc\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T14:22:15.129Z\">2.22pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>Keith Vaz</strong>, the Labour chair of the home affairs committee, congratulates May on killing off &quot;the UK Backlogs Agency&quot;.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5151aee3b5795d794abf44db\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T14:21:24.153Z\">2.21pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>May is responding to Cooper.</p> <p>She says Cooper&apos;s response was typically negative.</p> <p>Cooper should apologise for the mess left by Labour, she says.</p> <p>She says Cooper recently announced new immigration policy. But it involved setting up a task force.</p> <p>May says she will return to the Commons at a later date to give more details of the reorganisation.</p> <p>She says this decision has been taken after &quot;many, many hours of serious work&quot; over several months.</p> <p>She is not just restructuring UKBA because of Monday&apos;s home affairs committee report. If she restructured it every time it was criticised by the committee, she would be reorganising it every three months.</p> <p>Cooper does not have a plan, she says. Labour is not serious. The public knows that you cannot trust Labour on immigration.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-3e00c074-9d60-4e9f-aee1-ee19997d86f1\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/3/26/1364307677321/-460x276.png\" alt=\"Theresa May\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Theresa May Photograph: /BBC Parliament</span> </figcaption> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5151ad74b5795d794abf44d8\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T14:15:16.121Z\">2.15pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>Yvette Cooper</strong> is responding for Labour now.</p> <p>She says this is a rushed announcement.</p> <p>Labour has some sympathy for what May is trying to do, she says.</p> <p>But the problem is that the difficulties with UKBA have got worse under May.</p> <p>Cooper says May has already split UKBA once - into the border agency, and the Border Force.</p> <p>Queues at the borders went up, she says.</p> <p>There has been a 20% increase in the backlog of asylum cases in three months.</p> <p>She says May, and her cuts, are to blame for what went wrong with UKBA last year.</p> <p>She has cut its budget by more than 30% since the election.</p> <p>How much will these reforms cost?</p> <p>How many more illegal immigrants will be deported as a result?</p> <p>When May was in opposition, she said she was &quot;sick and tired&quot; of ministers who just blamed others when things went wrong.</p> <p>Does May now accept she is to blame?</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5151ac0095cbbc3a59c25e97\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T14:09:04.557Z\">2.09pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>May says one of the problems with UKBA was its computer system. The computer system will be reviewed.</p> <p><strong>• An immigration bill will be introduced in the next session of parliament, May says.</strong></p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5151abcc95cbbc3a59c25e96\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T14:08:12.711Z\">2.08pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>Theresa May</strong> is speaking now.</p> <p>She says the Border Force has been working more effectively since it was split from the UK Border Agency last year.</p> <p>The peformance of UKBA is &quot;not good enough&quot;. The home affairs committee has published many critical reports on it.</p> <p>It was never suited to deal with the way immigration numbers rose under Labour.</p> <p><strong>• May says the UK Border Agency is being split up.</strong></p> <p><strong>• Two new organisations will replace it: an immigration and visa service, and an immigration and law enforcement organisation.</strong></p> <p><strong>• Both new bodies will not have agency status. </strong>They will be part of the Home Office, and will report to ministers.</p> </div>   <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T14:22:34.458Z\">at 2.22pm GMT</time></p>  </div> <div id=\"block-5151aa0995cbbc3a59c25e93\" class=\"block is-summary\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T14:00:41.350Z\">2.00pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">Theresa May's statement on the UK Border Agency</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Theresa May, the home secretary, is about to make a statement about the future of the UK Border Agency.</p> <p>I will be focusing on the May statement now, not George Osborne at the Treasury committee as planned.</p> <p>There is speculation that May will effectively abolish UKBA, by gettting the Home Office to take over its functions.</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/home-affairs-committee/news/130325-ukba-report-published/\">On Monday the Commons home affairs committee published a blistering report on its performance. </a>Here&apos;s what Keith Vaz, the chairman of the committee, said at the time.</p> <blockquote> <p>“Successive UKBA Chief Executives have presided over chaos including 150 boxes of unopened mail, 100,000 unopened letters and yet another effective amnesty for thousands due to calamitous inefficiency.</p> <p>For six years the committee was misled by UKBA Chiefs about the agency’s unacceptable performance. It appears more like the scene of a Whitehall farce then a government agency operating in the 21st century.</p> <p>No sooner is one backlog closed, than four more are discovered. At this rate it will take 24 years to clear the backlog which still stands at the size of the population of Iceland. We were astonished to discover that MPs and applicants had been writing about cases yet 59,000 applications had not even been loaded onto the Agency’s computers. </p> <p>We are worried that given UKBA’s poor record of being transparent with the committee, the delays we know about could only be the tip of the iceberg. UKBA must publish a definitive list of all its backlogs and senior staff should not receive any bonuses until the backlogs are cleared.</p> </blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5151a69795cbbc3a59c25e8e\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T13:45:59.363Z\">1.45pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Here&apos;s some reaction to the Mid Staffs statement.</p> <p>From <strong>Norman Lamb</strong>, the Lib Dem health minister</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>[The new duty of candour] is a Liberal Democrat manifesto commitment that we are delivering on in Coalition. Poor care is simply unacceptable and staff at every level have a professional duty to speak up about it – and we will support them in doing so.</p> <p>The last Labour government ignored calls from the Liberal Democrats and campaigners to introduce a duty of candour.</p> <p>The new statutory duty of candour sends a very clear message about the importance of transparency and openness in the NHS.</p> </blockquote> <p>From<strong> Andy Burnham</strong>, the shadow health secretary</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Whilst we welcome much of what the Health Secretary has said today, it falls short of the full response to the Francis Report that the Prime Minister promised last month.</p> <p>Robert Francis made a very clear case for a new system of regulation of healthcare assistants to improve basic standards. Yet this didn’t feature in today’s response. Labour supports moves to rebalance nurse training to include more hands-on experience, but safe staffing is the glaring omission today. We will never get the right culture on our wards if they are understaffed and over-stretched.</p> <p>Things are already going in the wrong direction - the Care Quality Commission has recently reported that 1 in 10 hospitals in England do not have adequate staffing levels and just last week figures showed that there had been a reduction of 843 nurses between November and December last year. It is difficult for the NHS to deliver the standard of care that we all expect when there are now 5,000 fewer nurses. In last week’s Budget, the Department of Health handed £2.2bn from the NHS budget back to the Treasury - surely that money would have been better invested in the front-line and bringing all hospitals in England back up to safe staffing levels.</p> </blockquote> <p>From <strong>Mark Jones</strong>, head of the department of adult nursing at City University London</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Mr Hunt has called for &quot;Front-line, hands-on caring experience and values need to be equal with academic training.” But this is already a feature of our three year nursing degrees which have a 50/50 split between academic education and clinical practice experience.</p> </blockquote> <p>From <strong>Liz Kendall,</strong> the shadow care minister</p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/leicesterliz/status/316542031352696832\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>V partial, pick &amp; mix response to Francis Report. Plus real risk all emphasis on Chief Inspector of Hospitals makes NHS look 'up' not 'out'</p>&mdash; Liz Kendall MP (@leicesterliz) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/leicesterliz/status/316542031352696832\">March 26, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/leicesterliz/status/316543956420800512\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>V top down, centralised response to Francis Report from Jeremy Hunt. All about regulation, Chief Hospital Inspector \"will be responsible\"</p>&mdash; Liz Kendall MP (@leicesterliz) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/leicesterliz/status/316543956420800512\">March 26, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/leicesterliz/status/316544710346952704\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Partial on duty of candour; nothing on stronger voice for patients/public (real probs w local Healthwatch); ignores staff:patient ratios</p>&mdash; Liz Kendall MP (@leicesterliz) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/leicesterliz/status/316544710346952704\">March 26, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5151a34095cbbc3a59c25e8b\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T13:31:44.404Z\">1.31pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>The Hunt statement is now over.</p> <p>Here&apos;s an extract from<a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/the-government-s-response-to-the-francis-report\"> his opening statement.</a></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>To prevent problems arising in the first place, we need to embed a culture of zero harm and compassionate care throughout our NHS. A culture in which the needs of patients are central, whatever the pressures of a busy, modern health service.</p> <p>As Robert Francis said: &quot;The system as a whole failed in its most essential duty – to protect patients from unacceptable risks of harm and from unacceptable, and in some cases inhumane, treatment that should never be tolerated in any hospital.&quot;</p> <p>At the heart of this problem, the current definitions of success for hospitals fail to prioritise the needs of patients. Too often the focus has been on compliance with regulation rather than on what those regulations aim to achieve. Furthermore, the way hospitals are inspected is fundamentally flawed, with the same generalist inspectors looking at slimming clinics, care homes and major teaching hospitals – sometimes in the same month ...</p> <p>We must also build a culture of zero-harm throughout the NHS. This does not mean there will never be mistakes, just as a safety-first culture in the airline industry does not mean there are no plane crashes. But it does mean an attitude to harm which treats it as totally unacceptable and takes enormous trouble to learn from mistakes ...</p> <p>The events at Stafford Hospital were a betrayal of the worst kind. A betrayal of the patients, of the families, and of the vast majority of NHS staff who do everything in their power to give their patients the high-quality, compassionate care they deserve.</p> <p>But I want Mid Staffs not to be a byword for failure, but a catalyst for change.</p> <p>To create an NHS where everyone can be confident of safe, high quality, compassionate care.</p> <p>Where best practice becomes common practice.</p> <p>And where the way a person is made to feel as a human being is every bit as important as the treatment they receive.</p> </blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5151a02d95cbbc3a59c25e88\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T13:18:42.742Z\">1.18pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Here is a summary of the main points in the announcement. I have taken the text from <a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/news/putting-patients-first-government-publishes-response-to-francis-report\">the Department of Health&apos;s news release.</a></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>A culture of zero harm</p> <ul> <li>There will be a new regulatory model under a strong, independent Chief Inspector of Hospitals.</li> </ul> <ul> <li>The Chief Inspector will introduce single aggregated ratings. The Nuffield Trust rightly said that in organisations as large and complex as hospitals a single rating on its own could be misleading. The Chief Inspector will also develop ratings of hospital performance at department level. This will mean that cancer patients will be told of the quality of cancer services, and prospective mothers the quality of maternity services.</li> </ul> <ul> <li>The Chief Inspector of Hospitals will assess hospital complaints procedures.</li> </ul> <ul> <li>The CQC will move to a new specialist model based on rigorous and challenging peer-review. Assessments will include judgements about hospitals’ overall performance including whether patients are listened to and treated with dignity and respect, the safety of services, responsiveness, clinical standards and governance.</li> </ul> <ul> <li>A new Chief Inspector of Social Care will ensure the same rigour is applied across the health and care system. The merits of having a Chief Inspector of Primary Care are also being explored.</li> </ul> <ul> <li>The NHS Confederation will review how we can reduce the bureaucratic burden on frontline staff and NHS providers by a third.</li> </ul> <p>Detecting problems quickly</p> <ul> <li>A new statutory duty of candour will ensure honesty and transparency are the norm in every organisation overseen by the CQC.</li> </ul> <ul> <li>The new Chief Inspector of Hospitals will be the nation’s whistleblower- in-chief.</li> </ul> <ul> <li>Publishing survival results improves standards, as has been shown in heart surgery. Survival rates for a further 10 disciplines, including cardiology, vascular and orthopaedic surgery will now be published.</li> </ul> <p>Deal with problems quickly.</p> <p>• A new set of fundamental standards will be introduced to make explicit the basic rights that anyone should expect of the NHS. They will be produced by the Chief Inspector of Hospitals, working with NICE, patients and the public.</p> <p>• Where these standards are breached, a new failure regime will ensure that firm action is taken swiftly. If it is not, the failure regime could lead to special administration with the automatic suspension of the Board.</p> <p>Accountability</p> <ul> <li>Health and social care professionals will be held more accountable.</li> </ul> <ul> <li>We will consider the introduction of legal sanctions at a corporate level for providers who knowingly generate misleading information or withhold information from patients or relatives.</li> </ul> <ul> <li>The General Medical Council, the Nursing and Midwifery Council and the other professional regulators have been asked to tighten and speed up their procedures for breaches of professional standards.</li> </ul> <ul> <li>The Chief Inspector of Hospitals will also ensure that hospitals are meeting their existing legal obligations to ensure that unsuitable healthcare assistants are barred.</li> </ul> <p>Leadership</p> <ul> <li>NHS-funded student nurses will spend up to a year working on the frontline as healthcare assistants, as a prerequisite for receiving funding for their degree. This will ensure the people who become nurses have the right values and understand their role.</li> </ul> <ul> <li>Nurses’ skills will then be revalidated, as doctors’ are now, to ensure their skills remain up to date and fit for purpose.</li> </ul> <ul> <li>Healthcare support workers and adult social care workers will now have a code of conduct and minimum training standards, both of which are published today: <a href=\"http://www.skillsforhealth.org.uk/about-us/news/code-of-conduct-and-national-minimum-training-standards-for-healthcare-support-workers/\">www.skillsforhealth.org.uk/codeofconductandtrainingstandards</a></li> </ul> <ul> <li>The Chief Inspector will ensure that hospitals are properly recruiting, training and supporting healthcare assistants, drawing on the recommendations being produced by Camilla Cavendish.</li> </ul> <ul> <li>The Department of Health will become the first department where every civil servant will gain real and extensive experience of the frontline.</li> </ul> </blockquote> </div>   <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T13:23:35.184Z\">at 1.23pm GMT</time></p>  </div> <div id=\"block-51519e6cb5795d794abf44d0\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T13:11:08.532Z\">1.11pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Asked how will pay for the extra year that nurses have to spend as healthcare assistants, Hunt says the government will pilot this scheme, so that nurse training does inaccessible to applicants because of the cost.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51519db195cbbc3a59c25e87\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T13:08:01.261Z\">1.08pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>Bill Cash</strong>, a Conservative, says Sir David Nicholson should resign as NHS chief inspector because of his role in Mid Staffs.</p> <p>Hunt says he does not agree with Cash on this point.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51519d8795cbbc3a59c25e86\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T13:07:19.242Z\">1.07pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Labour&apos;s <strong>Barbara Keeley</strong> accuses Hunt of ignoring the issue of staffing levels.</p> <p>Hunt says he is not ignoring this issue. And he quotes from something Andy Burnham told the Francis inquiry. Burnham said central government could not mandate particular staffing levels, Hunt says.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51519d17b5795d794abf44ce\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T13:05:27.953Z\">1.05pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>Margot James,</strong> a Conservative, says that at Mid Staffs different staff gave very different standards of care. That shows it is not just a matter of resources, she says.</p> <p>Hunt agrees, although he says that sometimes resources are important.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51519c6c95cbbc3a59c25e85\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T13:02:36.721Z\">1.02pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/news/putting-patients-first-government-publishes-response-to-francis-report\">Here&apos;s the Department of Health&apos;s news release about its response to the Francis report.</a></p> <p><a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/the-government-s-response-to-the-francis-report\">And here&apos;s the full text of the statement that Hunt gave to MPs.</a></p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51519be395cbbc3a59c25e84\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T13:00:19.150Z\">1.00pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>On the Today programme this morning Peter Walsh, from the group Action Against Medical Accidents, said he hoped that Hunt would agree to impose a statutory duty of candour. This is what Walsh said.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>If [Hunt] does accept it, it&apos;s probably the biggest advance in patient safety and patients&apos; rights in the history of the NHS. For over 60 years the NHS has done no more than pay lip service to the fundamental principle that if something goes wrong and a patient is harmed the health service should be open and honest about it. It&apos;s a cancer, if you like, that has been eating away at the NHS, it creates a culture of cover up and denial, which permits and tolerates bullying and intimidation of whistleblowers, as well as dishonesty with patients.</p> </blockquote> <p>An MP asks Hunt about Walsh&apos;s comments.</p> <p>Hunt says he heard them. But he repeats the point about not wanting to take a decision yet about accepting a duty of candour that would apply to individuals until he receives the findings of a review covering protecting patients that will report later this year.</p> </div>   <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T13:01:26.315Z\">at 1.01pm GMT</time></p>  </div> <div id=\"block-51519b2eb5795d794abf44cc\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T12:57:18.829Z\">12.57pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Hunt says he would not expect any manager involved in the kind of things that happened at Mid Staff to ever be employed in the NHS again.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51519ac4b5795d794abf44cb\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T12:55:33.160Z\">12.55pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-4b14293c-c507-4c9c-8aa5-27c461dce25c\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/3/26/1364302523734/-460x276.png\" alt=\"Jeremy Hunt\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Jeremy Hunt Photograph: /BBC Parliament</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Hunt is responding to Burnham.</p> <p>He says Burnham should have apologised for Labour&apos;s targets culture, for not having a proper regulatory structure and for missing the warning signs.</p> <p>This was not just the darkest day in the NHS. It was the darkest day in Labour&apos;s management of the NHS.</p> <p>On the duty of candour, Hunt says staff already have a contractual duty of candour. But he has not yet decided to accept Francis&apos;s recommendation about the legal duty of candour applying to individuals because he does not want discourage a culture of openness (ie, individuals might not speak up if they think they might be prosecuted). Hunt says this matter is still be considered, and he will await the outcome of a review that is going on.</p> <p>On regulating healthcare assistants, Hunt says this could become a &quot;box ticking exercise&quot; because it would involve a database with from 5000,000 to 1.5m names on it.</p> <p>Hunt says Burnham himself refused to set up this public inquiry.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5151996095cbbc3a59c25e82\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T12:49:37.026Z\">12.49pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-ace1badd-b1e9-48a6-a6eb-cb06b058e626\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/3/26/1364301945723/-460x276.png\" alt=\"Andy Burnham\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Andy Burnham Photograph: /BBC Parliament</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>On the duty of candour, Burnham asks why it will not apply to individuals.</p> <p>And he asks if it will apply to all providers, including private ones.</p> <p>On patient voice, he asks if there will be a separate role for Healthwatch.</p> <p>Burnham asks if the government has accepted the case for healthcare assistants to be regulated.</p> <p>If nurses have to train as healthcare assistants, will there be people there to change them?</p> <p>Burnham says, according to the CQC, one in 10 hospitals do not have adequate staffing levels.</p> <p>Don&apos;t patients need a benchmark, so they can challenge staffing ratios. Will the government accept the Francis recommendations on staffing levels.</p> <p>He says Jeremy Hunt underspend last year by £2bn. Wouldn&apos;t it be better to spend the money on more staff?</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51519850b5795d794abf44c8\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T12:45:04.545Z\">12.45pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>Andy Burnham</strong>, the shadow health secretary, is replying.</p> <p>He says the NHS must learn from its mistakes.</p> <p>Today&apos;s reponse is not a full response, he says.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-515197fa95cbbc3a59c25e80\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T12:43:38.295Z\">12.43pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Hunt is concluding.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>I want Mid Staffs to be not a byword for failure, but a catalyst for change.</p> </blockquote> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-515197e095cbbc3a59c25e7f\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T12:43:12.680Z\">12.43pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Hunt says everyone working in the NHS must recognise they are part of a team.</p> <p>Student nurses will have to spend up to a year on the front line working as healthcare support workers, or assistants. This will become a prerequisite of obtaining funding.</p> <p>The Department of Health will become the first department where every civil servant will have real experience of the front line.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5151978eb5795d794abf44c7\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T12:41:50.413Z\">12.41pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Hunt says what went wrong at Mid Staffs was not typical of the NHS.</p> <p>The system must not crush the decency of most people in the NHS.</p> <p>He says the main problems at Mid Staffs were with the board. There will be new penalties for executives who withhold important information.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-51519738b5795d794abf44c6\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T12:40:24.890Z\">12.40pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Hunt says in future concerns must be acted upon.</p> <p>Trusts will be given only a limited amount of time to remedy problems.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-5151970295cbbc3a59c25e7e\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T12:39:30.365Z\">12.39pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Hunt says a new statutory duty of candour will be introduced for providers.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-515196c395cbbc3a59c25e7d\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T12:38:27.438Z\">12.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Hunt says he has asked the NHS Confederation to consider how paperwork in the NHS can be reduced by a third.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-515196a695cbbc3a59c25e7c\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T12:37:58.996Z\">12.37pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Hunt says at Mid Staffs the system failed. It did not protect patients from &quot;inhumane&quot; treatment in some cases.</p> <p>The way hospitals are inspected is flawed. Generalists inspectors inspect slimming clinics and major hospitals.</p> <p>A new inspectorate will be set up under the Care Quality Commission (CQC).</p> <p>Every trust will get a single rating. Patient experience will be at the heart of this.</p> <p>Hospitals will also be measured on a department by department basis.</p> <p>There must be a culture of zero harm in the NHS.</p> <p>That does not mean there will be no mistakes. But it does mean that harm will be treated as totally unacceptable. A review of how this could be established is underway.</p> </div>   <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T12:39:54.037Z\">at 12.39pm GMT</time></p>  </div> <div id=\"block-515195d295cbbc3a59c25e7a\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T12:34:26.936Z\">12.34pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Jeremy Hunt is starting his statement.</p> <p>He says Robert Francis QC produced a &quot;seminal report that will, I believe, mark a turning point in the history of the NHS&quot;.</p> <p>Terrible things happened at Mid Staffs, he says.</p> <p>He says he is announcing today the government&apos;s response to key recommendations in the report. A fuller response will be published later.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-515193c3b5795d794abf44c1\" class=\"block is-summary\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T12:25:39.624Z\">12.25pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">Jeremy Hunt's statement on the Mid Staffs report</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>Jeremy Hunt</strong>, the health secretary, will be announcing the government&apos;s formal response to the 290 recommendations in the Francis report on the Mid Staffs hospital trust scandal at 12.30pm.</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/blog/2013/feb/06/mid-staffordshire-nhs-trust-inquiry-report-published-live\">Here&apos;s the live blog that we ran on the day the Francis report was published.</a></p> <p>And here&apos;s a summary of key points from the Francis report, which I&apos;ve taken from that blog.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p><strong>• Causing death or harm to a patient should be a criminal offence, Robert Francis says.</strong></p> <p><strong>• A “duty of candour” should be imposed on NHS staff.</strong></p> <p><strong>• Everyone having hands-on care of a patient should be properly trained and registered.</strong></p> <p><strong>• Senior NHS staff who breach the code of conduct should be disqualified.</strong></p> <p><strong>• Accurate, useful and relevant information should be shared between everyone who needs it.</strong></p> <p><strong>• This scandal cannot be dealt with by sacking “scapegoats” and reorganising the NHS again, Francis says.</strong></p> <p><strong>• The business of the NHS system was put ahead of the wellbeing of patients, he says. </strong>Multiple failures by a wide array of organisations and individuals across “the NHS system” allowed poor care to persist.</p> <p><strong>• The Mid Staffs trust board was weak and did not listen to patients and staff, Francis says. </strong>There was a “serious failure” of its duties by the trust’s board of directors.</p> <p><strong>• This is a story of appalling and unnecessary suffering, he says. </strong></p> <p><strong>• He is calling for a &quot;zero tolerance&quot; approach to poor standards of care.</strong></p> <p><strong>• Francis calls for the creation of in effect one new super-regulator for the NHS which would scrutinise both clinical and financial standards. </strong>These tasks are currently performed by two watchdogs, the Care Quality Commission and Monitor.</p> </blockquote> </div>   <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T12:26:14.944Z\">at 12.26pm GMT</time></p>  </div> <div id=\"block-51518ce195cbbc3a59c25e72\" class=\"block is-summary\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T12:13:58.858Z\">12.13pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>   <h2 class=\"block-title\">Lunchtime summary</h2>  <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p><strong>•<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2013/mar/26/east-coast-mainline-return-private-sector\"> Patrick McLoughlin, the transport secretary, has announced that the East Coast mainline will be re-privatised</a>. </strong>(See <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/blog/2013/mar/26/hunt-mid-staffs-osborne-budget-live#block-5151727795cbbc3a59c25e5d\">10.09am</a> and <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/blog/2013/mar/26/hunt-mid-staffs-osborne-budget-live#block-5151781695cbbc3a59c25e60\">10.27am.)</a></p> <p><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2013/mar/26/uk-search-and-rescue-bristow\">The Department for Transport has announced that a Texas-based firm is to take over the operation of the UK&apos;s search and rescue helicopter service that has been mainly carried out by the RAF and Royal Navy for more than half a century</a>.</strong></p> <p><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-21933791\">Ruth Davidson, the leader of the Scottish Conservatives, has given a speech saying that the Scottish parliament should have more control over tax</a>.</strong> She said that Lord Strathclyde, the former leader of the Lords, would head a party commission considering what further powers could be devolved to Holyrood. Here&apos;s some Twitter comment from David Torrance, a commentator on Scottish politics.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/davidtorrance/status/316508638862790656\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>With benefit of hindsight, Ruth Davidson believes the Scottish Tories found themselves \"on the wrong side of history\" by opposing devo in 97</p>&mdash; David Torrance (@davidtorrance) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/davidtorrance/status/316508638862790656\">March 26, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/davidtorrance/status/316510090448470016\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>If Ruth Davidson's speech has bn cleared by Downing St (&amp; pres it has) then it can be taken as sign UKG is inching towards &gt; fiscal autonomy</p>&mdash; David Torrance (@davidtorrance) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/davidtorrance/status/316510090448470016\">March 26, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/davidtorrance/status/316512500222943233\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Ruth Davidson's speech a clear attempt to counter SNP claims voting \"no\" means no more devo. LDs have already done the same, just Lab left.</p>&mdash; David Torrance (@davidtorrance) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/davidtorrance/status/316512500222943233\">March 26, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/davidtorrance/status/316517501586513920\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>I'm usually a cynic but @<a href=\"https://twitter.com/ruthdavidsonmsp\">ruthdavidsonmsp</a> speech on more devo was coherent, well thought through &amp; went much further than I expected <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search/%23indyref\">#indyref</a></p>&mdash; David Torrance (@davidtorrance) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/davidtorrance/status/316517501586513920\">March 26, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure>  <p><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/2013/mar/26/lords-reject-jobcentre-sanctions-targets\">Peers have rejected proposals for an inquiry into whether the Department for Work and Pensions sanctions regime specifically covers whether jobcentre managers are given targets to get people off benefits or sanctioned</a>.</strong></p> <p><strong>• The Home Office has announced that Theresa May will make a statement in the Commons later on the beleaguered UK Border Agency.</strong> As the Press Association reports, the substance of the statement is unknown but sources within Parliament said it was expected to be &quot;significant&quot;. The statement, expected at around 2.15pm, comes after the home affairs committee warned that it would take 24 years to clear a backlog the size of the population of Iceland of asylum and immigration cases at the UKBA.</p> </div>   </div> <div id=\"block-515187a6b5795d794abf44b7\" class=\"block\" data-block-contributor=\"\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-03-26T11:33:58.554Z\">11.33am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p>    <div class=\"block-elements\">  <p>Robert Chote, chair of the Office for Budget Responsibility, and his OBR colleague Steve Nickell have been giving evidence to the Commons Treasury committee this morning. Sky&apos;s Joey Jones has been following the proceedings.</p>  <figure class=\