s-trust","type":"keyword","sectionId":"society","sectionName":"Society","webTitle":"Mid Staffordshire NHS Trust","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/society/mid-staffordshire-nhs-trust","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/society/mid-staffordshire-nhs-trust","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","type":"type","webTitle":"Article","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"profile/dick-vinegar","type":"contributor","webTitle":"Dick Vinegar","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/profile/dick-vinegar","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/profile/dick-vinegar","references":[],"bio":"<p>Dick Vinegar writes a regular column for the <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/healthcare-network\">Guardian Healthcare Professionals Network</a> on his experiences as an elderly patient. He writes under a pseudonym</p>","firstName":"","lastName":"vinegar"}],"fields":{"headline":"How will nurses and their leaders respond to the Francis report?","standfirst":"The Patient from Hell takes a look at how the Royal College of Nursing dealt with the fallout from the Mid Staffordshire scandal","trailText":"<p>The Patient from Hell takes a look at how the Royal College of Nursing dealt with the fallout from the Mid Staffordshire scandal</p>","byline":"Dick Vinegar","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-image-406167281\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/3/21/1363876815318/Nurse-008.jpg\" alt=\"Nurse\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">The Francis report was tough on nurses and their leaders, says Dick Vinegar Photograph: Christopher Furlong/Getty Images</span> </figcaption> </figure>","body":"<p>After GPs, nurses are the most important people I meet on a care pathway.</p> <p>On any ward or clinic, it is nurses who welcome me, show me compassion and empathy, and see me through the treatments the doctors mete out. Hospital doctors sweep in their white coats, wave their magic wands, and sweep out again. They may do the curing, but it is the nurses who the patient remembers from their stay in hospital. This is why the standard of nursing has to be high, and why the appalling care received by the patients at Stafford is a debacle for the whole NHS.</p> <p>Inquiry chairman Robert Francis QC was tough on nurses and particularly their leaders in his report. &quot;At Stafford, <a href=\"http://www.rcn.org.uk/\" title=\"\">the Royal College of Nursing</a> (RCN) was ineffective both as a professional representative organisation and as a trade union. Little was done to uphold professional standards among nursing staff or to address concerns and problems being faced by its members.</p> <p>He added: &quot;A prime reason for this was the lack of effective representation from elected officers on site. Further, the support available from RCN officials at a regional and national level was limited.&quot;</p> <p>The <a href=\"http://www.midstaffspublicinquiry.com/report\" title=\"\">report</a> is peppered with words like &quot;poor leadership, tolerance of poor standards, inadequate staffing levels, recruitment and training&quot;. Staff at Mid Staffs &quot;received only ineffective representation of concerns from the RCN&quot;. These criticisms were not just made about Mid Staffs. On 15 March, Ann Clwyd MP followed up her devastating attack on the nursing treatment her dying husband received at the University of Wales hospital in Cardiff, by saying that <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-21785732\" title=\"\">she had received 2,000 letters and emails from all over the UK</a>, with similar stories. If I were a leader of the RCN faced with such comments, I would go into a corner and hide.</p> <p>But not the leadership of the RCN. Its response seemed to shovel off most of the blame for Mid Staffs onto others who imposed inadequate staffing levels. &quot;There are important lessons that we all need to learn from the Francis inquiry, but surely one of the first is that trusts cannot be allowed to let staffing levels, particularly clinical posts such as nurses, fall to unsafe levels&quot;.</p> <p>So, it&apos;s not me guv; it&apos;s those nasty hospital managers. But, surely, it is the job of the RCN, to ensure that staffing levels are adequate for nursing standards to be maintained? The RCN welcomed Francis&apos;s recommendation for the registration and regulation of healthcare assistants. But it would, wouldn&apos;t it? One of Francis&apos;s main concerns about the RCN was that &quot;there is a concerning potential for conflict between the RCN&apos;s professional role of promoting high standards in nursing, and its union role of negotiating terms and conditions and defending members&apos; material and other narrow interests.&quot; The RCN has agreed to look into this, but I sense that its heart is not in it. It is altogether too big a change to contemplate.</p> <p>Indeed, the RCN&apos;s whole response is not focusing on Francis&apos;s damning criticisms about compassion and its failure to support or listen to the concerns of nurses at Mid Staffs. It appears to be in denial. I believe the leadership&apos;s response shows that it will be incapable of making the necessary changes called for by Francis. Bureaucrats do not change their spots.</p> <p>They must all resign. This is not scapegoating. Their initial response to Francis shows that they are not up to the massive task of splitting the RCN into two independent bodies – one for nursing standards and one a trade union. While on the subject of resignation, I announce my solidarity with <a href=\"http://www.itv.com/news/update/2013-02-28/julie-bailey-we-want-his-resignation-if-not-his-sacking/\" title=\"\">Julie Bailey&apos;s campaign for the resignation of Sir David Nicholson</a>. Patients and their families have to stick together, particularly as the leaders of the medical profession, a string of former health secretaries and the prime minister have sprung to his defence. My own slant on Sir David is to compare him with <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2012/dec/28/british-approach-falklands-neglect-hope\" title=\"\">Lord Carrington, who resigned when the Argentinians invaded the Falklands in 1982</a>. For him it was a matter of honour, a quality absent from our political masters nowadays. </p> <p>PS: A neighbour, visiting her brother-in-law aged 93 in hospital last weekend, found him in a filthy condition. The nurses did jump to when she complained, but she should not have had to complain. The spirit of Mid Staffs lives on for the old in hospital. The RCN and the nursing profession have a massive mountain to climb. They do not appear to have the empathy, the will or the leadership skills to reach the top of that mountain.</p> <p><strong>This article is published by Guardian Professional. </strong><a href=\"https://register.theguardian.com/healthcare-professionals/\" title=\"\"><strong>Join the Healthcare Professionals Network</strong></a><strong> to receive regular emails and exclusive offers.</strong></p>","wordcount":"791","commentCloseDate":"2013-04-08T07:30:00Z","commentable":"true","creationDate":"2013-03-21T13:02:49Z","internalComposerCode":"569669f2e4b0f2d1f22cf631","internalOctopusCode":"7389390","internalPageCode":"1883669","isPremoderated":"false","lastModified":"2013-03-25T09:36:06Z","newspaperEditionDate":"2013-03-25T00:00:00Z","productionOffice":"UK","publication":"theguardian.com","shortUrl":"https://gu.com/p/3etze","shouldHideAdverts":"false","showInRelatedContent":"true","legallySensitive":"false","lang":"en","internalRevision":"1","internalShortId":"/p/3etze"},"apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/healthcare-network/2013/mar/25/mid-staffordshire-scandal-royal-college-of-nursing","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/healthcare-network/2013/mar/25/mid-staffordshire-scandal-royal-college-of-nursing","webTitle":"How will nurses and their leaders respond to the Francis report?","webPublicationDate":"2013-03-25T08:30:00Z","sectionName":"Healthcare Professionals Network","sectionId":"healthcare-network","type":"article","id":"healthcare-network/2013/mar/25/mid-staffordshire-scandal-royal-college-of-nursing","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"section":{"id":"healthcare-network","webTitle":"Healthcare Professionals Network","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/healthcare-network","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/healthcare-network","editions":[{"id":"healthcare-network","webTitle":"Healthcare Professionals Network","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/healthcare-network","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/healthcare-network","code":"default"}]},"isHosted":false}},{"metadata":{"id":"internal-code/page/1885938","articleType":"article","group":"included"},"content":{"references":[{"id":"rich-link/https://www.theguardian.com/info/2015/dec/08/daily-email-uk","type":"rich-link"}],"elements":[{"id":"gu-image-406272345","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/3/26/1364320743128/Nurses-to-face-hands-on-s-008.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"Nurses to face hands on stint","caption":"The health secretary, Jeremy Hunt, address the Commons. Few of his proposed changes to the NHS relate to increasing accountability to patients, argues Roger Taylor. Photograph: PA","credit":"Photograph: Pa Wire/PA","photographer":"Pa Wire","source":"PA","width":"460","height":"276","secureFile":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/3/26/1364320743128/Nurses-to-face-hands-on-s-008.jpg","displayCredit":"false","mediaId":"gu-image-406272345","imageType":"Photograph"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-406272346","relation":"thumbnail","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/3/26/1364320736700/Nurses-to-face-hands-on-s-003.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"Nurses to face hands on stint","caption":"Health secretary Jeremy Hunt address the Commons. Few of his proposed reforms relate to increasing accountability to patients. Photograph: PA","credit":"Photograph: Pa Wire/PA","photographer":"Pa Wire","source":"PA","width":"140","height":"84","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/3/26/1364320736700/Nurses-to-face-hands-on-s-003.jpg","displayCredit":"false","mediaId":"gu-image-406272346","imageType":"Photograph"}}]}],"tags":[{"id":"commentisfree/commentisfree","type":"blog","sectionId":"commentisfree","sectionName":"Opinion","webTitle":"Opinion","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/commentisfree","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/commentisfree","references":[]},{"id":"society/nhs","type":"keyword","sectionId":"society","sectionName":"Society","webTitle":"NHS","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/society/nhs","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/society/nhs","references":[]},{"id":"society/mid-staffordshire-nhs-trust","type":"keyword","sectionId":"society","sectionName":"Society","webTitle":"Mid Staffordshire NHS Trust","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/society/mid-staffordshire-nhs-trust","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/society/mid-staffordshire-nhs-trust","references":[]},{"id":"politics/jeremy-hunt","type":"keyword","sectionId":"politics","sectionName":"Politics","webTitle":"Jeremy Hunt","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/politics/jeremy-hunt","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/politics/jeremy-hunt","references":[]},{"id":"tone/comment","type":"tone","webTitle":"Comment","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/tone/comment","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/tone/comment","references":[]},{"id":"society/society","type":"keyword","sectionId":"society","sectionName":"Society","webTitle":"Society","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/society/society","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/society/society","references":[]},{"id":"politics/politics","type":"keyword","sectionId":"politics","sectionName":"Politics","webTitle":"Politics","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/politics/politics","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/politics/politics","references":[]},{"id":"uk/uk","type":"keyword","sectionId":"uk-news","sectionName":"UK news","webTitle":"UK news","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/uk/uk","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/uk/uk","references":[{"id":"rich-link/https://www.theguardian.com/info/2015/dec/08/daily-email-uk","type":"rich-link"}]},{"id":"type/article","type":"type","webTitle":"Article","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"profile/roger-taylor","type":"contributor","webTitle":"Roger Taylor","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/profile/roger-taylor","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/profile/roger-taylor","references":[],"bio":"<p>Roger Taylor is co-founder and director of research at <a href=\"http://drfosterintelligence.co.uk/\">Dr Foster Intelligence</a> and author of <a href=\"http://www.guardianbookshop.co.uk/BerteShopWeb/viewProduct.do?ISBN=9780571303649&amp;INTCMP=mic_866\">God Bless the NHS</a> (Faber &amp; Faber)</p>","bylineImageUrl":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/3/26/1364317937293/Roger-Taylor.jpg","firstName":"roger","lastName":"taylor"}],"fields":{"headline":"Jeremy Hunt's dangerous belief in a single 'truth' about hospitals","standfirst":"The government's response to the Mid Staffs report addresses regulators first and patients second. This has to be reversed","trailText":"<strong>Roger Taylor:</strong> The government's response to the Mid Staffs report addresses regulators first and patients second. This has to be reversed","byline":"Roger Taylor","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-image-406272345\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/3/26/1364320743128/Nurses-to-face-hands-on-s-008.jpg\" alt=\"Nurses to face hands on stint\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">The health secretary, Jeremy Hunt, address the Commons. Few of his proposed changes to the NHS relate to increasing accountability to patients, argues Roger Taylor. Photograph: PA</span> </figcaption> </figure>","body":"<p>Imagine if you lived in a world in which there was a single metric that defined the &quot;truth&quot; about the &quot;good quality&quot; of a car. Imagine if the career progression of car designers depended on how well they scored on this miraculous metric. It is hard to picture exactly what mode of transport we would all be using but it would, without doubt, be a worse world to live in.</p> <p>This is not an attack on Which? or What Car? that regularly line up cars on various league tables of quality. They are very useful publications. It is an illustration of what was probably the most absurd part of Jeremy Hunt&apos;s <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/mar/26/failing-hospitals-nhs-jeremy-hunt\" title=\"\">statement</a> in response to the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/feb/06/mid-staffs-hospital-francis-report\" title=\"\">Francis report </a>on Mid Staffordshire NHS Foundation Trust.</p> <p>He promised us that &quot;in the future the chief inspector will ensure that there is a single version of the truth about how their hospitals are performing, not just on finance and targets, but on a single assessment that fully reflects what matters to patients&quot;.</p> <p>In itself, having a single official assessment of how well hospitals are performing is a perfectly sensible idea and should be welcomed. Indeed, most of what Hunt proposed was welcome and should, if executed effectively, go a long way to addressing the problems that occurred in Mid Staffordshire</p> <p>But there was a problem in the way he presented this particular aspect of his plans – one that risks repeating the failures of the past, one that reeks of the old NHS culture: the culture that led to the tragedies at Mid Staffordshire.</p> <p>A single assessment can be a useful tool. But not if you begin to believe it is the &quot;truth&quot; about quality or that you have made &quot;an assessment that fully reflects what matters to patients&quot;. After all, there are roughly 50 million NHS patients in England, ranging from infants to old people with dementia. You might be able to fully reflect what matters to some of them; or partially reflect what matters to all of them. But, as Abraham Lincoln would have said, had he worked in the NHS, you are never going to assess all of what matters to all of them.</p> <p>Hunt has identified quite rightly that we need more expert inspectors, more detailed information on quality, and regulators that exercise real judgments about where care is being provided to a good standard. But if quality in healthcare is not to be reduced once again to a tick-box exercise, we must avoid a world in which large central government agencies are tasked with identifying the &quot;single version of the truth&quot; when it comes to quality in healthcare.</p> <p>In Hunt&apos;s statement, most of the proposed changes related to increasing accountability upwards to regulators and government. Relatively few – such as the duty of candour – related to accountability directly to patients. This is pragmatic, in that it will have the biggest immediate effect. But it ignores the essential longer-term goal of increasing accountability directly to patients.</p> <p>Francis had some good ideas on how to achieve this. Unfortunately, they appear rather late in the report. That may be why they seem to have been ignored. It is a shame because they point towards a much more radical rebalancing of power and accountability in healthcare.</p> <p>Recommendation 244 says: &quot;Patients need to be granted user-friendly, real-time and retrospective access to read their records, and a facility to enter comments. They should be enabled to have a copy of records in a form usable by them, if they wish to have one.&quot; And: &quot;Systems should be designed to include prompts and defaults where these will contribute to safe and effective care, and to accurate recording of information on first entry.&quot;</p> <p>I want an NHS in which information about the standards of care I receive come to me first and regulators second. Currently we are building an NHS that does this the other way round. This needs to be reversed.</p>","wordcount":"670","commentCloseDate":"2013-03-29T18:15:19Z","commentable":"true","creationDate":"2013-03-26T17:49:15Z","internalComposerCode":"5685b7c0e4b0741a0d9c1239","internalOctopusCode":"7410647","internalPageCode":"1885938","isPremoderated":"false","lastModified":"2016-07-19T16:27:36Z","newspaperEditionDate":"2013-03-26T00:00:00Z","productionOffice":"UK","publication":"theguardian.com","shortUrl":"https://gu.com/p/3emvf","shouldHideAdverts":"false","showInRelatedContent":"true","legallySensitive":"false","lang":"en","internalRevision":"11","internalShortId":"/p/3emvf"},"apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2013/mar/26/jeremy-hunt-hospitals-mid-staffs","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/mar/26/jeremy-hunt-hospitals-mid-staffs","webTitle":"Jeremy Hunt's dangerous belief in a single 'truth' about hospitals | Roger Taylor","webPublicationDate":"2013-03-26T18:15:19Z","sectionName":"Opinion","sectionId":"commentisfree","type":"article","id":"commentisfree/2013/mar/26/jeremy-hunt-hospitals-mid-staffs","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"section":{"id":"commentisfree","webTitle":"Opinion","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree","editions":[{"id":"commentisfree","webTitle